f=Cybersecurity/cortex/custom/security-monitoring/SKILL.md · in=live watch over business's security posture ingesting alerts detection rules, triaging them severity, managing response runbook, ensuring nothing falls through cracks. Combines **Elastic Security MCP** (tool-level SIEM workflows, alert triage, case management) **Incident Commander** (severity classification, runbook integration, communication templates, post-incident reviews). **Tool workflow from:** Elastic Security MCP. **Severity/runbook framework from:** Incident Commander. integration custom. · p=Security monitoring turns raw alerts managed incidents. Without structured triage process, alerts pile up, real incidents get buried noise, severity inconsistent. skill provides discipline triage consistently, classify accurately, respond systematically. · wu=alert fires SIEM., detection rule needs triage queueing., incident's severity needs classification., runbook needs executed known scenario., Post-incident review needs conducted. · h2:Severity Classification (Incident Commander framework)=\| Severity \| Definition \| Response Time \| Escalation \| · h2:Severity Classification (Incident Commander framework)=\|---\|---\|---\|---\| · h2:Severity Classification (Incident Commander framework)=\| **SEV1** \| Critical impact — active breach, data exfiltration, production compromise \| Immediate (≤15 min) \| Full IR team + operator notified \| · h2:Severity Classification (Incident Commander framework)=\| **SEV2** \| High impact — confirmed compromise of non-critical system, credential theft, malware detected \| ≤1 hour \| IR lead + system owner \| · h2:Severity Classification (Incident Commander framework)=\| **SEV3** \| Moderate impact — suspicious activity, policy violation, potential indicator \| ≤4 hours \| Assigned analyst \| · h2:Severity Classification (Incident Commander framework)=\| **SEV4** \| Low impact — minor anomaly, informational, false positive candidate \| ≤24 hours \| Triage queue \| · st:/ Protocol=`ALERT INGEST (from detection-engineering rules, SIEM, or external feeds) \· → TRIAGE (Elastic workflow: fetch → investigate → classify) \· → CLASSIFY per Incident Commander severity: SEV1 / SEV2 / SEV3 / SEV4 \· → ASSIGN runbook (if known scenario) or escalate \· → DOCUMENT in case management (Elastic cases)` · h3:Phase Triage (Elastic workflow)=**Fetch investigate.** Pull alert SIEM. Check event details, related entities (host, user, IP), historical context. **Classify.** True positive, false positive, further investigation needed. **For true positives:** Open case, add observables, classify severity Incident Commander matrix. **For false positives:** Consider tuning detection rule. Log tuning signal. · h3:Phase Classify Severity (Incident Commander matrix)=**Assign severity using SEV1–SEV4 matrix.** conservative: doubt between two severities, choose higher one. **Notify severity.** SEV1/SEV2 require immediate escalation operator relevant system owners. · h3:Phase 3 — Respond=**Run existing runbook scenario matches.** Known malware family, phishing pattern, beacon follow established runbook. **If runbook exists:** Document novel scenario, apply containment best practices (all actions: operator-run security-inversion), flag runbook development. **All containment actions operator-executed.** cortex detects, classifies, recommends containment; operator runs isolation, credential reset, network block. · h3:Phase 4 — Document=10. **Case management.** SEV2+ incident gets Elastic case timeline, investigation notes, actions taken, evidence collected. 11. **Post-incident review (Incident Commander).** After SEV1/SEV2: timeline reconstruction, communication log, what went well, what went wrong, action items. · of=`## Security Monitoring: [alert/incident ID] \· Type: [triage / severity-classification / runbook / post-incident] \· Severity: [SEV1/SEV2/SEV3/SEV4] \· Confidence: [high/medium/low] \· Method: [Elastic MCP triage → Incident Commander severity] \· Runbook: [matched / none — flag for development]` · pr=**Triage alert, classify incident.** alert ignored; incident left unclassified., **Severity impact, volume.** SEV1 SEV1 whether it's one alert 50., **Known scenarios get runbooks; unknowns get escalation.**, **cortex detects recommends; operator contains.** security-inversion holds response., **Every SEV2+ gets post-incident review.** post-mortem, learning. · f=SIEM access manual monitoring log, labeled "manual SIEM." Flag risk warden., Elastic MCP skill use Incident Commander framework alone, labeled "without SIEM integration reasoning-based.", Incident Commander skill use Elastic MCP alone general severity mapping, labeled "provisional severity framework." · b:with Other Skills=**detection-engineering** (sibling): detection rules generate alerts skill triages; tuning feedback flows back., **security-incident-response** (sibling): SEV1/SEV2 incidents escalate IR; skill handles triage, handles response., **threat-hunting** (sibling): hunts generate leads become monitoring alerts., **bastion**: network anomalies detected feed bastion's network security reviews., **ops (Engineering)**: joint security+reliability incident (e.g., ransomware) coordinates through process., **warden**: monitoring gaps, untuned rules, missed SLAs register risks.